title: Elastic scattering of 27.5 MeV alpha particles on 27Al, 28Si, 32S,Ti and 59Co nuclei and the r0 discrete ambiguity of the optical potential.

27Al, 28Si, 32S,Ti and 59Co nuclei and the r0
discrete ambiguity of the optical potential.

x4freetext: The energy of the incident beam was measured
by means of the differential absorption method. The
absolute reliability of this measurement was checked
by the kinematic method.
Thirteen semiconductor detectors were mounted
on four rotatable arms. Particles scaterred at extreme
backward angles up to 179 degrees were detected by
means of a special very narrow counter. Angular
resolution of the back scattering counter was about
+-0.1 degree while for the others was +-0.5 degree.
Silicon surface barrier counters with the
thickness of the depletion layer of 0.5 mm were used.
A special arrangement was provided to prepare targets
by evaporation inside of the vacuum store.
The targets were located at the distance of about 12 m
from the cyclotron. The diameter of the targets was
about 30 mm.
During the cross-section measurements the thickness
of the target was checked by a special semiconductor
monitor viewing the target at a fixed angle of about
30 degrees (lab).
The intensity of the alpha-particle beam was monitored
in two independent ways in order to ensure the proper
normalization of the cross-section. The total charge
in the Faraday cup was measured by a standart current
integrator.
In addition the beam intensity was monitored by two
semiconductor detectors counting alpha particles
scattered from a gold foil placed in the beam in front
of the Faraday cup.

x4freetext: Error of the absolute value of the cross-
section
The relative errors in the values of the experimental
differential cross-section vary from 1% to 10 % in deep
minima.
Numerical results including realtive errors of
individual measurements are available in Report 624/PL
of the Institute of Nuclear Physics in Cracow.
